Mechanics of the heart as a pump 

Tuesday, April 4, 2017 

5:41 PM 

Describe the mechanical events of the cardiac cycle.  

The atria work as weak "primer pumps" for the ventricles. Cardiac output from the left heart = cardiac output from the right heart (~5L/min). However, the right ventricle (~27 mmHg systolic at rest) is much weaker and normally generates much less pressure than the left ventricle (~120mmHg systolic at rest). 

 

Cardiac cycle 

Mechanically, the cardiac cycle consists of: 

-systole, the myocardial contraction and ejection of blood from the cardiac chamber 

-diastole, the myocardial relaxation in filling of the chambers 

 

The atria and ventricles never contract at the same time, although they are able to relax at the same time. 

Alternate names for the phases: 

1, Filling phase- initially passive due to the raised venous pressure (80% of blood volume into the relaxed ventricles at rest), then due to atrial contractions (adds 20% more volume to ventricles at rest) 

2, Isometric/Isovolumic ventricular contraction phase- all 4 valves closed, intraventricular pressure increases but no blood is ejected and contracting ventricular muscle cannot shorten 

3, Ejection phase: semilunar valves open and blood is ejected from ventricles, first 1/3 ejects 70% of stroke volume, last 2/3 ejects the rest. 

4, Isometric/Isovolumic ventricular relaxation phase, all 4 cardiac valves are closed 

 

Note that stroke volume = end diastolic volume - end systolic volume. Ventricles do not fully empty during systole. Normal SV ~ 70ml.  

 

 

 

 

 

Heart sounds 

As ventricular pressure rises, the closed AV valves cause a back-surging of blood which causes vibrations heard as the first heart sound. Likewise, back-surging pulmonary arterial and aortic blood bounces off the closed semilunar valves to cause the second heart sound. 

 

Draw a ventricular pressure volume loop and label the events of the cardiac cycle. 

 

Describe Starling's Law and its role in keeping the output of the left and right ventricles. 

Starling's Law states that the stroke volume of the heart increases in response to an increase in the volume of blood filling the heart, when all other factors remain constant. A larger volume of blood flows into the ventricle, stretching the walls of the heart, causing a greater expansion during diastole, which in turn increases the force of the contraction and thus the quantity of blood that is pumped into the aorta during systole.  

 

Ventricular stretch can include: a change in myocardial fiber length, a change in end-diastolic volume of the ventricle, or a change in filling pressure of the ventricle. 

 

The heart automatically pumps the same volume of blood out of the ventricles as comes in to the heart during the previous ventricular diastole so that output is automatically matched to equal input. This is an intrinsic feature of the heart which occurs independent of neural or hormonal control. It also ensures that cardiac output from both ventricles is equal.
